{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17490899","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17490899"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"answeredAt":null,"options":[],"response":null,"finalizedAt":null},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"777"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}},{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17490942","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17490942"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T05:24:14+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T05:24:14+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"777"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"777","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/777"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.05,0.02,0.81,0.08,0.04]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"777"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"97847"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"777","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/777"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"777"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"80397"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"27"},{"type":"tags","id":"34"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"2637"},{"type":"tags","id":"2843"},{"type":"tags","id":"9051"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"7894"},{"type":"contributions","id":"7910"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"97847","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/97847"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EAn otherwise well 64-year-old electrician presents with a six week history of pain on movement of his left elbow. He cannot recall any precipitating event or trigger. His medical history is unremarkable. He has been continuing to work since the pain started, but finds it bothersome.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination his blood pressure is 132/86 mmHg, pulse 65/min, respiratory rate 12/min and temperature 36.5\u00b0C. There is swelling at the left elbow (Image). The area is mildly warm to touch and active extension of the elbow is limited to 160 degrees. There is pain on active and passive flexion and extension.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Septic arthritis with abscess","Haematoma","Olecranon bursitis","Acute gout flare","Epicondylitis"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOlecranon bursitis\u003C/strong\u003E is the most likely diagnosis, given the characteristic swelling over the posterior elbow, with a 6-week duration of pain, pain on passive movement, reduction of active range of movement, occupational risk factors, and otherwise systemic wellness. Chronic pressure on the bursa, such as from leaning on elbows, is a common cause of microtrauma and inflammation to the site.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESeptic arthritis\u003C/strong\u003E is unlikely as he is systemically well and he has no risk factors for bone or joint infection (type 2 diabetes, recent surgery, joint replacement/repair, acute trauma, broken skin). However, the swelling should still be monitored for signs of infection, e.g. increasing area of erythema, severity of pain, warmth and tenderness, as it can complicate bursitis later.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe absence of an acute traumatic event, discolouration, and the 6-week duration of swelling make a \u003Cstrong\u003Ehaematoma\u003C/strong\u003E unlikely. Haemorrhagic bursitis may occur spontaneously (without acute trauma) if a patient is on anticoagulants, but this patient is not.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAcute gout flares\u003C/strong\u003E can present with swelling, pain, warmth and erythema, but the severity of pain is often disabling, peaking within 24 hours of onset, and gradually resolve over the next 7-14 days - not persistent over 6 weeks.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe pronounced swelling at the joint and pain on passive movement is not characteristic of epicondylitis. \u003Cstrong\u003EEpicondylitis \u003C/strong\u003Eis often caused by chronic overuse of the elbow joint resulting in inflammation/damage of muscles e.g. extensor carpi radialis brevis (in lateral epicondylitis) and the common flexor tendon + its muscles (in medial epicondylitis). The chronic, persistent history of pain, risk factors, and clinical presentation can be similar to that of bursitis.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Bursitis is often caused by chronic microtrauma (e.g. from overuse in an occupation or sport) or an acute traumatic event.","In the diagnosis of bursitis, joint infection is an important complication to exclude and to continue monitoring for."],"references":["Blackwell JR, Hay BA, Bolt AM, Hay SM. Olecranon bursitis: a systematic overview. Shoulder Elbow [Internet]. 2014;6(3):182-190. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC4935058/. doi: 10.1177/1758573214532787","Pangia J, Rizvi TJ. Olecranon Bursitis. StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2022. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK470291/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"80397"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"777"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"18734"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"18734","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/m